          <section class=3D"prose">
            <h2>Why ancient Greek units are tricky</h2>
            <p>Unlike modern SI, ancient Greek measures were <em>not fully =
standardized</em>. Athens could use one value, another polis a slightly dif=
ferent one, and over the centuries values drifted. So in this tool we:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>picked the most cited Attic/Classical values,</li>
              <li>rounded to a sensible number of decimals,</li>
              <li>and clearly tell you it=E2=80=99s an approximation.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>How the converter works</h3>
            <p>For each category we choose a modern SI base (meters, kilogr=
ams, liters). We store each ancient unit as a multiplier of that base. When=
 you convert:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>your value is turned into the SI base,</li>
              <li>and then into the target ancient unit.</li>
            </ol>

            <h2>FAQ</h2>
            <h3>1. I found a different value for the stadion. Who=E2=80=99s=
 right?</h3>
            <p>Both may be. Some sources put a stadion near 180 m, others a=
 bit above 185 m. Our 184.8 m follows 600 =C3=97 0.308 m.</p>
            <h3>2. Can I add my own unit?</h3>
            <p>You can copy the JavaScript and add your unit with your pref=
erred factor.</p>
            <h3>3. Is this okay for museum labels?</h3>
            <p>Use your institution=E2=80=99s standard, but you can test va=
lues here first.</p>
